ANTHRAX, BISON - CANADA (05): (NORTHWEST TERRITORIES)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 12 Jul 2010
Source: HQYellowknife.com [edited]
<http://hqyellowknife.com/news/5987/Bison%20death%20toll%20at%2037%20in%20anthrax%20outbreak/>


The Dept. of Environment and Natural Resources continues to battle an
outbreak of anthrax in bison in the Slave River Lowlands. Officials
have now found 37 carcasses in the region, up from 7 found in late June 2010.

A spokesperson with ENR, Judy McLinton, says that every day, crews
are taking measures to contain the outbreak. "Once a carcass is
found, we have a team go in, and the site where the bison carcass is
found is treated with formaldehyde as well as the carcass," she said.
"And part of that is to just make sure that scavengers can't get at
it or get anthrax as well."

She says disposal teams then go in and burn the carcasses; on
average, they're dealing with 3 dead bison a day in the Slave River
Lowlands. She says they continue to do surveillance flights over the
lowlands and the Mackenzie Bison Sanctuary.

Typically, ENR crews monitor the area until mid-August, as bison
contract anthrax during the hot summer months when they wallow in the
sand and inhale spores contaminated with the bacteria. [I wish it was
as easy as this, because if it were so, all they would have to do is
disinfect each wallow. - Mod.MHJ]

There have been 14 outbreaks of anthrax in the Slave River Lowlands
and Wood Buffalo National Park between 1962 and 2007.

--
