ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[2]
Date: 14 Jul 2010
From: Troy Ellsworth <Troy_Ellsworth@gov.nt.ca>


Operations are normal, just treating and burning as fast as we can;
it is actually 38 carcasses as of late yesterday [13 Jul 2010].

There is no cluster per se, but there are 2 hot spots (extreme north
and south ends) with carcasses spread out in between -- they are
spread all over the Hook Lake range -- east of the Slave River.

--
Troy Ellsworth
Manager, Wildlife, South Slave Region,
Government of the NWT
Department of Environment & Natural Resources Highway #5, Fort Smith, NT
Canada X0E 0P0
<Troy_Ellsworth@gov.nt.ca>

[Our thanks to Troy. While those on the ground may make light of
their skills, I would ask our members to consider the actual
situation with 38 sites: One or 2 with new freshly dead; those
treated with formaldehyde awaiting burning; others under bonfire
construction; fires burning; and fires out/old dealt-with carcasses;
trying to make sense of it; and look for any new dead carcasses and
any missed carcasses, all of which is a complex and very demanding situation.

With carcasses spread out like this, and even allowing for the
ambling abilities of wood bison, it strikes me that biting flies are
the major culprit. And so far, it is not unlike the 1993 epidemic in
the Mackenzie Sanctuary. Normally, such epidemics last around 3
weeks, maybe 10 percent of the exposed bison will die, and some 90
percent of the survivors will have significant serological evidence
of subclinical infections. The good news is that, thanks to the
efficient handling of the '93 epidemic (all but a handful of the 175+
carcasses were burnt) and the immunological protection provided, the
disease has not been seen since in that sanctuary. And maybe the
Slave River Lowlands herds will similarly benefit from this 2010
epidemic. - Mod.MHJ]
